==English==
===Etymology===
[[Category:Greek derivations]]
From [[Ancient Greek]] '''[[εμπάθεια]]''' (''empatheia'') "affection, passion for someone", from '''[[εμπαθής]]''' (''empathes'') "in a state of emotion", from prefix '''[[εμ-]]''' 
(''em-''), variant of '''[[εν-]]''' (''en-''), "in, at", from '''[[έν]]''' (''en'') "in, within, on, at, by" + '''[[παθέω]]''' (''patheo'') "to have a secondary affection", from '''[[πάσχω]]''' (''pascho'') "to receive an impression from without, to suffer"

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
'''empathy'''

# [[sympathetic]] [[identification]] and [[understanding]] of someone else's [[feeling]]s or [[motive]]s
# the intellectual identification of the thoughts, feelings, or state of another person
# [[pity]], [[compassion]] or [[commiseration]]

